data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — gives "Expected:3 Actual:2" on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use IsTrue with a message for predicate checks
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of != null
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | You already check for 3, so `> 0` is redundant |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer message: "Assert.IsNotNull failed" |
| `users.Single(...)` | `users.SingleOrDefault(...)` | `Single` throws an unhandled exception on failure instead of a clean test failure |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

```csharp
// Verify contents regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Verify exact order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Check membership
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, specificUser);

// Ensure all items are a given type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// No nulls in the collection
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// No duplicates
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
```

> **Note:** `CollectionAssert` works on `ICollection`, so you may need `.ToList()` if you have an `IEnumerable`.
